1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:01,402
Day 13.

2
00:00:01,402 --> 00:00:05,347
I lost 40 dollars to a position that didn't exist.

3
00:00:05,347 --> 00:00:08,875
My own bot had lied to me for five and a half hours.

4
00:00:08,875 --> 00:00:10,263
I can't code.

5
00:00:10,263 --> 00:00:12,375
9 years in crypto.

6
00:00:12,375 --> 00:00:14,569
AI trades my thousand.

7
00:00:14,569 --> 00:00:15,944
Day 13.

8
00:00:15,944 --> 00:00:18,013
The bot hit a stop loss.

9
00:00:18,013 --> 00:00:20,875
Fired a market sell to close the long.

10
00:00:20,875 --> 00:00:23,083
From its point of view — closed.

11
00:00:23,083 --> 00:00:27,138
Problem was — the order it sent to Coinbase had no close flag.

12
00:00:27,138 --> 00:00:30,388
The exchange treated it as a brand new short.

13
00:00:30,388 --> 00:00:31,344
Result?

14
00:00:31,344 --> 00:00:32,930
Long got netted.

15
00:00:32,930 --> 00:00:34,541
Short got opened.

16
00:00:34,541 --> 00:00:39,222
Five and a half hours later I opened the app manually and found it.

17
00:00:39,222 --> 00:00:42,013
What scared me wasn't the 40 dollars.

18
00:00:42,013 --> 00:00:46,083
It was — every monitor I had said everything was fine.

19
00:00:46,083 --> 00:00:48,250
The bot's logs said okay.

20
00:00:48,250 --> 00:00:49,719
Risk said okay.

21
00:00:49,719 --> 00:00:52,986
You could only see the ghost from outside the system.

22
00:00:52,986 --> 00:00:57,708
The most dangerous kind of failure is the one that doesn't announce itself.

23
00:00:57,708 --> 00:01:01,277
It doesn't crash, doesn't error, doesn't warn.

24
00:01:01,277 --> 00:01:04,861
It just quietly makes your numbers slightly wrong.

25
00:01:04,861 --> 00:01:09,527
Day 14 tomorrow — I fixed it with 3 lines of code.

26
00:01:09,527 --> 00:01:10,986
Follow along.

